# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sqlalchemy-core
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] A **database transaction** symbolizes a unit of work, performed within a database management system (or similar system) against a database, that is treated in a coherent and reliable way independent of other transactions.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] A transaction generally represents any change in a database.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] To provide isolation between programs accessing a database concurrently.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] If this isolation is not provided, the programs' outcomes are possibly erroneous.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] In a database management system, a transaction is a single unit of logic or work, sometimes made up of multiple operations.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] Any logical calculation done in a consistent mode in a database is known as a transaction.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] One example is a transfer from one bank account to another: the complete transaction requires subtracting the amount to be transferred from one account and adding that same amount to the other.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] Database practitioners often refer to these properties of database transactions using the acronym ACID.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] Databases and other data stores which treat the integrity of data as paramount often include the ability to handle transactions to maintain the integrity of data.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] A single transaction consists of one or more independent units of work, each reading and/or writing information to a database or other data store.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] When this happens it is often important to ensure that all such processing leaves the database or data store in a consistent state.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] Examples from double-entry accounting systems often illustrate the concept of transactions.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] In double-entry accounting every debit requires the recording of an associated credit.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] A transactional system would make both entries pass or both entries would fail.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] By treating the recording of multiple entries as an atomic transactional unit of work the system maintains the integrity of the data recorded.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] In other words, nobody ends up with a situation in which a debit is recorded but no associated credit is recorded, or vice versa.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] A **transactional database** is a DBMS that provides the ACID properties for a bracketed set of database operations (begin-commit).
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] Transactions ensure that the database is always in a consistent state, even in the event of concurrent updates and failures.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] All the write operations within a transaction have an all-or-nothing effect, that is, either the transaction succeeds and all writes take effect, or otherwise, the database is brought to a state that does not include any of the writes of the transaction.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] Transactions also ensure that the effect of concurrent transactions satisfies certain guarantees, known as isolation level.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] The highest isolation level is serializability, which guarantees that the effect of concurrent transactions is equivalent to their serial (i.e. sequential) execution.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] Most modern relational database management systems support transactions.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] NoSQL databases prioritize scalability along with supporting transactions in order to guarantee data consistency in the event of concurrent updates and accesses.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] In a database system, a transaction might consist of one or more data-manipulation statements and queries, each reading and/or writing information in the database.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] Users of database systems consider consistency and integrity of data as highly important.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] Execute a set of data manipulations and/or queries.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] If no error occurs, then commit the transaction.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] If an error occurs, then roll back the transaction.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] A transaction commit operation persists all the results of data manipulations within the scope of the transaction to the database.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] A transaction rollback operation does not persist the partial results of data manipulations within the scope of the transaction to the database.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] In no case can a partial transaction be committed to the database since that would leave the database in an inconsistent state.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] Internally, multi-user databases store and process transactions, often by using a transaction ID or XID.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] There are multiple varying ways for transactions to be implemented other than the simple way documented above.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] Nested transactions, for example, are transactions which contain statements within them that start new transactions (i.e. sub-transactions).
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] *Multi-level transactions* are a variant of nested transactions where the sub-transactions take place at different levels of a layered system architecture (e.g., with one operation at the database-engine level, one operation at the operating-system level).
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] Another type of transaction is the compensating transaction.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] Transactions are available in most SQL database implementations, though with varying levels of robustness.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] For example, MySQL began supporting transactions from early version 3.23, but the InnoDB storage engine was not default before version 5.5.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] The earlier available storage engine, MyISAM does not support transactions.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] A transaction is typically started using the command `BEGIN` (although the SQL standard specifies `START TRANSACTION`).
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] When the system processes a `COMMIT` statement, the transaction ends with successful completion.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] A `ROLLBACK` statement can also end the transaction, undoing any work performed since `BEGIN`.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] If autocommit was disabled with the start of a transaction, autocommit will also be re-enabled with the end of the transaction.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] One can set the isolation level for individual transactional operations as well as globally.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] At the highest level (`READ COMMITTED`), the result of any operation performed after a transaction has started will remain invisible to other database users until the transaction has ended.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] At the lowest level (`READ UNCOMMITTED`), which may occasionally be used to ensure high concurrency, such changes will be immediately visible.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] Relational databases are traditionally composed of tables with fixed-size fields and records.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] Object databases comprise variable-sized blobs, possibly serializable or incorporating a mime-type.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] The fundamental similarities between Relational and Object databases are the start and the commit or rollback.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] After starting a transaction, database records or objects are locked, either read-only or read-write.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] Once the transaction is fully defined, changes are committed or rolled back atomically, such that at the end of the transaction there is no inconsistency.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] Database systems implement distributed transactions as transactions accessing data over multiple nodes.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] A distributed transaction enforces the ACID properties over multiple nodes, and might include systems such as databases, storage managers, file systems, messaging systems, and other data managers.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] In a distributed transaction there is typically an entity coordinating all the process to ensure that all parts of the transaction are applied to all relevant systems.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] Moreover, the integration of Storage as a Service (StaaS) within these environments is crucial, as it offers a virtually infinite pool of storage resources, accommodating a range of cloud-based data store classes with varying availability, scalability, and ACID properties.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] This integration is essential for achieving higher availability, lower response time, and cost efficiency in data-intensive applications deployed across cloud-based data stores.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] The Namesys Reiser4 filesystem for Linux supports transactions, and as of Microsoft Windows Vista, the Microsoft NTFS filesystem supports distributed transactions across networks.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/database-transaction] There is occurring research into more data coherent filesystems, such as the Warp Transactional Filesystem (WTF).
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] In object-oriented programming, data-management tasks act on objects that combine scalar values into objects.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] For example, consider an address book entry that represents a single person along with zero or more phone numbers and zero or more addresses.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] This could be modeled in an object-oriented implementation by a "Person object" with an attribute/field to hold each data item that the entry comprises: the person's name, a list of phone numbers, and a list of addresses.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] The list of phone numbers would itself contain "PhoneNumber objects" and so on.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] Each such address-book entry is treated as a single object by the programming language (it can be referenced by a single variable containing a pointer to the object, for instance).
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] Various methods can be associated with the object, such as methods to return the preferred phone number, the home address, and so on.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] By contrast, relational databases, such as SQL, group scalars into tuples, which are then enumerated in tables.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] Tuples and objects have some general similarity, in that they are both ways to collect values into named fields such that the whole collection can be manipulated as a single compound entity.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] They have many differences, though, in particular: lifecycle management (row insertion and deletion, versus garbage collection or reference counting), references to other entities (object references, versus foreign key references), and inheritance (non-existent in relational databases).
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] As well, objects are managed on-heap and are under full control of a single process, while database tuples are shared and must incorporate locking, merging, and retry.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] Object–relational mapping provides automated support for mapping tuples to objects and back, while accounting for all of these differences.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] The heart of the problem involves translating the logical representation of the objects into an atomized form that is capable of being stored in the database while preserving the properties of the objects and their relationships so that they can be reloaded as objects when needed.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] If this storage and retrieval functionality is implemented, the objects are said to be persistent.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] Implementation-specific details of storage drivers are generally wrapped in an API in the programming language in use, exposing methods to interact with the storage medium in a way which is simpler and more in line with the paradigms of surrounding code.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] The following is a simple example, written in C# code, to execute a query written in SQL using a database engine.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] In contrast, the following makes use of an ORM-job API which makes it possible to write code that naturally makes use of the features of the language.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] The case above makes use of an object representing the storage repository and methods of that object.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] Other frameworks might provide code as static methods, as in the example below, and yet other methods may not implement an object-oriented system at all.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] Often the choice of paradigm is made for the best fit of the ORM into the surrounding language's design principles.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] Compared to traditional techniques of exchange between an object-oriented language and a relational database, ORM often reduces the amount of code that needs to be written.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] Disadvantages of ORM tools generally stem from the high level of abstraction obscuring what is actually happening in the implementation code.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] Another approach is to use an object-oriented database management system (OODBMS) or document-oriented databases such as native XML databases that provide more flexibility in data modeling.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] OODBMSs are databases designed specifically for working with object-oriented values.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] Using an OODBMS eliminates the need for converting data to and from its SQL form, as the data is stored in its original object representation and relationships are directly represented, rather than requiring join tables/operations.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] The equivalent of ORMs for document-oriented databases are called object-document mappers (ODMs).
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] Document-oriented databases also prevent the user from having to "shred" objects into table rows.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] Many of these systems also support the XQuery query language to retrieve datasets.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] Object-oriented databases tend to be used in complex, niche applications.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] One of the arguments against using an OODBMS is that it may not be able to execute ad-hoc, application-independent queries.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] For this reason, many programmers find themselves more at home with an object-SQL mapping system, even though most object-oriented databases are able to process SQL queries to a limited extent.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] Other OODBMS provide replication to SQL databases, as a means of addressing the need for ad-hoc queries, while preserving well-known query patterns.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] A variety of difficulties arise when considering how to match an object system to a relational database.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] These difficulties are referred to as the object–relational impedance mismatch.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] An alternative to implementing ORM is use of the native procedural languages provided with every major database.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] These can be called from the client using SQL statements.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] The Data Access Object (DAO) design pattern is used to abstract these statements and offer a lightweight object-oriented interface to the rest of the application.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] ORMs are limited to their predefined functionality, which may not cover all edge cases or database features.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/object-relational-mapping] They usually mitigate this limitation by providing users with an interface to write raw queries, such as Django ORM.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] For new users who want to quickly see what basic ORM use looks like, here’s an abbreviated form of the mappings and examples used in the SQLAlchemy Unified Tutorial.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] The code here is fully runnable from a clean command line.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] As the descriptions in this section are intentionally **very short**, please proceed to the full SQLAlchemy Unified Tutorial for a much more in-depth description of each of the concepts being illustrated here.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] Changed in version 2.0: The ORM Quickstart is updated for the latest **PEP 484**-aware features using new constructs including `mapped_column()`.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] See the section ORM Declarative Models for migration information.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] Here, we define module-level constructs that will form the structures which we will be querying from the database.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] The mapping starts with a base class, which above is called `Base`, and is created by making a simple subclass against the `DeclarativeBase` class.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] Individual mapped classes are then created by making subclasses of `Base`.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] A mapped class typically refers to a single particular database table, the name of which is indicated by using the `__tablename__` class-level attribute.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] Next, columns that are part of the table are declared, by adding attributes that include a special typing annotation called `Mapped`.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] The name of each attribute corresponds to the column that is to be part of the database table.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] The datatype of each column is taken first from the Python datatype that’s associated with each `Mapped` annotation; `int` for `INTEGER`, `str` for `VARCHAR`, etc.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] Nullability derives from whether or not the `Optional[]` (or its equivalent) type modifier is used.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] More specific typing information may be indicated using SQLAlchemy type objects in the right side `mapped_column()` directive, such as the `String` datatype used above in the `User.name` column.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] The association between Python types and SQL types can be customized using the type annotation map.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] The `mapped_column()` directive is used for all column-based attributes that require more specific customization.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] Besides typing information, this directive accepts a wide variety of arguments that indicate specific details about a database column, including server defaults and constraint information, such as membership within the primary key and foreign keys.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] The `mapped_column()` directive accepts a superset of arguments that are accepted by the SQLAlchemy `Column` class, which is used by SQLAlchemy Core to represent database columns.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] All ORM mapped classes require at least one column be declared as part of the primary key, typically by using the `Column.primary_key` parameter on those `mapped_column()` objects that should be part of the key.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] In the above example, the `User.id` and `Address.id` columns are marked as primary key.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] Taken together, the combination of a string table name as well as a list of column declarations is known in SQLAlchemy as table metadata.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] Setting up table metadata using both Core and ORM approaches is introduced in the SQLAlchemy Unified Tutorial at Working with Database Metadata.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] The above mapping is an example of what’s known as Annotated Declarative Table configuration.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] Other variants of `Mapped` are available, most commonly the `relationship()` construct indicated above.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] In contrast to the column-based attributes, `relationship()` denotes a linkage between two ORM classes.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] In the above example, `User.addresses` links `User` to `Address`, and `Address.user` links `Address` to `User`.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] The `relationship()` construct is introduced in the SQLAlchemy Unified Tutorial at Working with ORM Related Objects.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] Finally, the above example classes include a `__repr__()` method, which is not required but is useful for debugging.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] Mapped classes can be created with methods such as `__repr__()` generated automatically, using dataclasses.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] More on dataclass mapping at Declarative Dataclass Mapping.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] The `Engine` is a **factory** that can create new database connections for us, which also holds onto connections inside of a Connection Pool for fast reuse.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] The `echo=True` parameter indicates that SQL emitted by connections will be logged to standard out.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] A full intro to the `Engine` starts at Establishing Connectivity - the Engine.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] A lot just happened from that bit of Python code we wrote.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] For a complete overview of what’s going on on with Table metadata, proceed in the Tutorial at Working with Database Metadata.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] We are now ready to insert data in the database.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] We accomplish this by creating instances of `User` and `Address` classes, which have an `__init__()` method already as established automatically by the declarative mapping process.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] We then pass them to the database using an object called a Session, which makes use of the `Engine` to interact with the database.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] It’s recommended that the `Session` be used in context manager style as above, that is, using the Python `with:` statement.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] The `Session` object represents active database resources so it’s good to make sure it’s closed out when a series of operations are completed.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] In the next section, we’ll keep a `Session` opened just for illustration purposes.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] Basics on creating a `Session` are at Executing with an ORM Session and more at Basics of Using a Session.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] Then, some varieties of basic persistence operations are introduced at Inserting Rows using the ORM Unit of Work pattern.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] With some rows in the database, here’s the simplest form of emitting a SELECT statement to load some objects.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] To create SELECT statements, we use the `select()` function to create a new `Select` object, which we then invoke using a `Session`.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] The above query also made use of the `Select.where()` method to add WHERE criteria, and also used the `ColumnOperators.in_()` method that’s part of all SQLAlchemy column-like constructs to use the SQL IN operator.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] More detail on how to select objects and individual columns is at Selecting ORM Entities and Columns.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] It’s very common to query amongst multiple tables at once, and in SQL the JOIN keyword is the primary way this happens.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] The above query illustrates multiple WHERE criteria which are automatically chained together using AND, as well as how to use SQLAlchemy column-like objects to create “equality” comparisons, which uses the overridden Python method `ColumnOperators.__eq__()` to produce a SQL criteria object.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] Some more background on the concepts above are at The WHERE clause and Explicit FROM clauses and JOINs.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] The `Session` object, in conjunction with our ORM-mapped classes `User` and `Address`, automatically track changes to the objects as they are made, which result in SQL statements that will be emitted the next time the `Session` flushes.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] Notice when we accessed `patrick.addresses`, a SELECT was emitted.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] Background on different ways to access related items using more or less SQL is introduced at Loader Strategies.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] A detailed walkthrough on ORM data manipulation starts at Data Manipulation with the ORM.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] All things must come to an end, as is the case for some of our database rows - here’s a quick demonstration of two different forms of deletion, both of which are important based on the specific use case.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] First we will remove one of the `Address` objects from the “sandy” user.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] When the `Session` next flushes, this will result in the row being deleted.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] This behavior is something that we configured in our mapping called the delete cascade.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] The last SELECT above was the lazy load operation proceeding so that the `sandy.addresses` collection could be loaded, so that we could remove the `sandy_address` member.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] There are other ways to go about this series of operations that won’t emit as much SQL.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] Next, we will delete the “patrick” user entirely.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] For a top-level delete of an object by itself, we use the `Session.delete()` method; this method doesn’t actually perform the deletion, but sets up the object to be deleted on the next flush.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] The `Session.delete()` method in this particular case emitted two SELECT statements, even though it didn’t emit a DELETE, which might seem surprising.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] This is because when the method went to inspect the object, it turns out the `patrick` object was expired, which happened when we last called upon `Session.commit()`, and the SQL emitted was to re-load the rows from the new transaction.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] This expiration is optional, and in normal use we will often be turning it off for situations where it doesn’t apply well.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] The Tutorial discusses ORM deletion at Deleting ORM Objects using the Unit of Work pattern.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] Background on object expiration is at Expiring / Refreshing; cascades are discussed in depth at Cascades.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] For a new user, the above sections were likely a whirlwind tour.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] There’s a lot of important concepts in each step above that weren’t covered.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] With a quick overview of what things look like, it’s recommended to work through the SQLAlchemy Unified Tutorial to gain a solid working knowledge of what’s really going on above.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/quickstart] 2007-2026, the SQLAlchemy authors and contributors.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] A **relational database** (**RDB**) is a database based on the relational model of data, as proposed by E.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] A Relational Database Management System (RDBMS) is a type of database management system that stores data in a structured format using rows and columns.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Many relational database systems are equipped with the option of using SQL (Structured Query Language) for querying and updating the database.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] The concept of relational database was defined by E.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Codd introduced the term *relational* in his research paper "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks".
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] In this paper and later papers, he defined what he meant by *relation*.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] One well-known definition of what constitutes a relational database system is composed of Codd's 12 rules.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Provide relational operators to manipulate the data in tabular form.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] In 1974, IBM began developing System R, a research project to develop a prototype RDBMS.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] The first system sold as an RDBMS was Multics Relational Data Store (June 1976).
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Oracle was released in 1979 by Relational Software, now Oracle Corporation.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Other examples of an RDBMS include IBM Db2, SAP Sybase ASE, and Informix.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] In 1984, the first RDBMS for Macintosh began being developed, code-named Silver Surfer, and was released in 1987 as 4th Dimension and known today as 4D.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] The most common definition of an RDBMS is a product that presents a view of data as a collection of rows and columns, even if it is not based strictly upon relational theory.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] By this definition, RDBMS products typically implement some but not all of Codd's 12 rules.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] A second school of thought argues that if a database does not implement all of Codd's rules (or the current understanding on the relational model, as expressed by Christopher J.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Date, Hugh Darwen and others), it is not relational.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] This view, shared by many theorists and other strict adherents to Codd's principles, would disqualify most DBMSs as not relational.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] For clarification, they often refer to some RDBMSs as *truly-relational database management systems* (TRDBMS), naming others *pseudo-relational database management systems* (PRDBMS).
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] As of 2009, most commercial relational DBMSs employ SQL as their query language.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Alternative query languages have been proposed and implemented, notably the pre-1996 implementation of Ingres QUEL.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] A relational model organizes data into one or more tables (or "relations") of columns and rows, with a unique key identifying each row.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Generally, each table/relation represents one "entity type" (such as customer or product).
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] The rows represent instances of that type of entity (such as "Lee" or "chair") and the columns represent values attributed to that instance (such as address or price).
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Each row in a table has its own unique key.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Rows in a table can be linked to rows in other tables by adding a column for the unique key of the linked row (such columns are known as foreign keys).
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Codd showed that data relationships of arbitrary complexity can be represented by a simple set of concepts.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Part of this processing involves consistently being able to select or modify one and only one row in a table.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Therefore, most physical implementations have a unique primary key (PK) for each row in a table.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] When a new row is written to the table, a new unique value for the primary key is generated; this is the key that the system uses primarily for accessing the table.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] System performance is optimized for PKs.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Other, more natural keys may also be identified and defined as alternate keys (AK).
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Often several columns are needed to form an AK (this is one reason why a single integer column is usually made the PK).
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Both PKs and AKs have the ability to uniquely identify a row within a table.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Additional technology may be applied to ensure a unique ID across the world, a globally unique identifier, when there are broader system requirements.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] The primary keys within a database are used to define the relationships among the tables.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] When a PK migrates to another table, it becomes a foreign key (FK) in the other table.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] When each cell can contain only one value and the PK migrates into a regular entity table, this design pattern can represent either a one-to-one or one-to-many relationship.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Most relational database designs resolve many-to-many relationships by creating an additional table that contains the PKs from both of the other entity tables – the relationship becomes an entity; the resolution table is then named appropriately and the two FKs are combined to form a PK.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] The migration of PKs to other tables is the second major reason why system-assigned integers are used normally as PKs; there is usually neither efficiency nor clarity in migrating a bunch of other types of columns.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Relationships are a logical connection between different tables (entities), established on the basis of interaction among these tables.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] These relationships can be modelled as an entity-relationship model.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] In order for a database management system (DBMS) to operate efficiently and accurately, it must use ACID transactions.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Part of the programming within an RDBMS is accomplished using stored procedures (SPs).
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Often procedures can be used to greatly reduce the amount of information transferred within and outside of a system.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] For increased security, the system design may grant access to only the stored procedures and not directly to the tables.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Fundamental stored procedures contain the logic needed to insert new and update existing data.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] More complex procedures may be written to implement additional rules and logic related to processing or selecting the data.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] The relational database was first defined in June 1970 by Edgar Codd, of IBM's San Jose Research Laboratory.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Codd's view of what qualifies as an RDBMS is summarized in Codd's 12 rules.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] A relational database has become the predominant type of database.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Other models besides the *relational model* include the hierarchical database model and the network model.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] In a relational database, a *relation* is a set of tuples that have the same attributes.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] A tuple usually represents an object and information about that object.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Objects are typically physical objects or concepts.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] A relation is usually described as a table, which is organized into rows and columns.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] All the data referenced by an attribute are in the same domain and conform to the same constraints.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] The relational model specifies that the tuples of a relation have no specific order and that the tuples, in turn, impose no order on the attributes.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Applications access data by specifying queries, which use operations such as *select* to identify tuples, *project* to identify attributes, and *join* to combine relations.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Relations can be modified using the *insert*, *delete*, and *update* operators.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] New tuples can supply explicit values or be derived from a query.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Similarly, queries identify tuples for updating or deleting.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] If the tuple contains a candidate or primary key then obviously it is unique; however, a primary key need not be defined for a row or record to be a tuple.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] The definition of a tuple requires that it be unique, but does not require a primary key to be defined.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Because a tuple is unique, its attributes by definition constitute a superkey.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] All data are stored and accessed via relations.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Relations that store data are called "base relations", and in implementations are called "tables".
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Other relations do not store data, but are computed by applying relational operations to other relations.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] These relations are sometimes called "derived relations".
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] In implementations these are called "views" or "queries".
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Derived relations are convenient in that they act as a single relation, even though they may grab information from several relations.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Also, derived relations can be used as an abstraction layer.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] A domain describes the set of possible values for a given attribute, and can be considered a constraint on the value of the attribute.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Mathematically, attaching a domain to an attribute means that any value for the attribute must be an element of the specified set.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] The character string *"ABC"*, for instance, is not in the integer domain, but the integer value *123* is.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Another example of domain describes the possible values for the field "CoinFace" as ("Heads","Tails").
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] So, the field "CoinFace" will not accept input values like (0,1) or (H,T).
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Constraints are often used to make it possible to further restrict the domain of an attribute.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] For instance, a constraint can restrict a given integer attribute to values between 1 and 10.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Constraints provide one method of implementing business rules in the database and support subsequent data use within the application layer.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] SQL implements constraint functionality in the form of check constraints.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Constraints restrict the data that can be stored in relations.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] These are usually defined using expressions that result in a Boolean value, indicating whether or not the data satisfies the constraint.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Constraints can apply to single attributes, to a tuple (restricting combinations of attributes) or to an entire relation.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Since every attribute has an associated domain, there are constraints (**domain constraints**).
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] The two principal rules for the relational model are known as **entity integrity** and **referential integrity**.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Every relation/table has a primary key, this being a consequence of a relation being a set.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] A primary key uniquely specifies a tuple within a table.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] While natural attributes (attributes used to describe the data being entered) are sometimes good primary keys, surrogate keys are often used instead.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] A surrogate key is an artificial attribute assigned to an object which uniquely identifies it (for instance, in a table of information about students at a school they might all be assigned a student ID in order to differentiate them).
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] The surrogate key has no intrinsic (inherent) meaning, but rather is useful through its ability to uniquely identify a tuple.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Another common occurrence, especially in regard to N:M cardinality is the composite key.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] A composite key is a key made up of two or more attributes within a table that (together) uniquely identify a record.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Foreign key refers to a field in a relational table that matches the primary key column of another table.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Foreign keys need not have unique values in the referencing relation.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] A foreign key can be used to cross-reference tables, and it effectively uses the values of attributes in the referenced relation to restrict the domain of one or more attributes in the referencing relation.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] A stored procedure is executable code that is associated with, and generally stored in, the database.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Stored procedures usually collect and customize common operations, like inserting a tuple into a relation, gathering statistical information about usage patterns, or encapsulating complex business logic and calculations.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Frequently they are used as an application programming interface (API) for security or simplicity.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Implementations of stored procedures on SQL RDBMS's often allow developers to take advantage of procedural extensions (often vendor-specific) to the standard declarative SQL syntax.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Stored procedures are not part of the relational database model, but all commercial implementations include them.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] An index is one way of providing quicker access to data.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Indices can be created on any combination of attributes on a relation.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Queries that filter using those attributes can find matching tuples directly using the index (similar to Hash table lookup), without having to check each tuple in turn.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] This is analogous to using the index of a book to go directly to the page on which the information you are looking for is found, so that you do not have to read the entire book to find what you are looking for.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Relational databases typically supply multiple indexing techniques, each of which is optimal for some combination of data distribution, relation size, and typical access pattern.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Indices are usually implemented via B+ trees, R-trees, and bitmaps.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Indices are usually not considered part of the database, as they are considered an implementation detail, though indices are usually maintained by the same group that maintains the other parts of the database.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] The use of efficient indexes on both primary and foreign keys can dramatically improve query performance.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] This is because B-tree indexes result in query times proportional to log(n) where n is the number of rows in a table and hash indexes result in constant time queries (no size dependency as long as the relevant part of the index fits into memory).
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Queries made against the relational database, and the derived relvars in the database are expressed in a relational calculus or a relational algebra.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] In his original relational algebra, Codd introduced eight relational operators in two groups of four operators each.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Other operators have been introduced or proposed since Codd's introduction of the original eight including relational comparison operators and extensions that offer support for nesting and hierarchical data, among others.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Normalization was first proposed by Codd as an integral part of the relational model.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] It encompasses a set of procedures designed to eliminate non-simple domains (non-atomic values) and the redundancy (duplication) of data, which in turn prevents data manipulation anomalies and loss of data integrity.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] The most common forms of normalization applied to databases are called the normal forms.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Connolly and Begg define database management system (DBMS) as a "software system that enables users to define, create, maintain and control access to the database".
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] RDBMS is an extension of that initialism that is sometimes used when the underlying database is relational.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] An alternative definition for a **relational database management system** is a database management system (DBMS) based on the relational model.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Most databases in widespread use today are based on this model.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] RDBMSs have been a common option for the storage of information in databases used for financial records, manufacturing and logistical information, personnel data, and other applications since the 1980s.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Relational databases have often replaced legacy hierarchical databases and network databases, because RDBMS were easier to implement and administer.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] However, due to the expanse of technologies, such as horizontal scaling of computer clusters, NoSQL databases have recently become popular as an alternative to RDBMS databases.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] Distributed Relational Database Architecture (DRDA) was designed by a workgroup within IBM in the period 1988 to 1994.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] DRDA enables network connected relational databases to cooperate to fulfill SQL requests.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] The messages, protocols, and structural components of DRDA are defined by the Distributed Data Management Architecture.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/relational-database] According to research company Gartner, in 2011, the five leading proprietary software relational database vendors by revenue were Oracle (48.8%), IBM (20.2%), Microsoft (17.0%), SAP including Sybase (4.6%), and Teradata (3.7%).
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] Introduced in the 1970s, SQL offered two main advantages over older read–write APIs such as ISAM or VSAM.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] Firstly, it introduced the concept of accessing many records with one single command.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] Secondly, it eliminates the need to specify *how* to reach a record, i.e., with or without an index.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] Originally based upon relational algebra and tuple relational calculus, SQL consists of many types of statements, which may be informally classed as sublanguages, commonly: data query language (DQL), data definition language (DDL), data control language (DCL), and data manipulation language (DML).
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] The scope of SQL includes data query, data manipulation (insert, update, and delete), data definition (schema creation and modification), and data access control.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] Although SQL is essentially a declarative language (4GL), it also includes procedural elements.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] SQL was one of the first commercial languages to use Edgar F.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] The model was described in his influential 1970 paper, "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks".
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] Despite not entirely adhering to the relational model as described by Codd, SQL became the most widely used database language.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] SQL became a standard of the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) in 1986 and of the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) in 1987.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] Since then, the standard has been revised multiple times to include a larger set of features and incorporate common extensions.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] Despite the existence of standards, virtually no implementations in existence adhere to it fully, and most SQL code requires at least some changes before being ported to different database systems.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] SQL was initially developed at IBM by Donald D.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] Boyce after learning about the relational model from Edgar F.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] This version, initially called SEQUEL (Structured English Query Language), was designed to manipulate and retrieve data stored in IBM's original quasirelational database management system, System R, which a group at IBM San Jose Research Laboratory had developed during the 1970s.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] Chamberlin and Boyce's first attempt at a relational database language was SQUARE (Specifying Queries in A Relational Environment), but it was difficult to use due to subscript/superscript notation.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] After moving to the San Jose Research Laboratory in 1973, they began work on a sequel to SQUARE.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] The original name SEQUEL, which is widely regarded as a pun on QUEL, the query language of Ingres, was later changed to SQL (dropping the vowels) because "SEQUEL" was a trademark of the UK-based Hawker Siddeley Dynamics Engineering Limited company.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] The label SQL later became the acronym for Structured Query Language.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] After testing SQL at customer test sites to determine the usefulness and practicality of the system, IBM began developing commercial products based on their System R prototype, including System/38, SQL/DS, and IBM Db2, which were commercially available in 1979, 1981, and 1983, respectively.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] IBM's endorsement caused the industry to move to SQL from alternatives like QUEL.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] In the late 1970s, Relational Software, Inc.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] (now Oracle Corporation) saw the potential of the concepts described by Codd, Chamberlin, and Boyce, and developed their own SQL-based RDBMS with aspirations of selling it to the U.S.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] Navy, Central Intelligence Agency, and other U.S. government agencies.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] In June 1979, Relational Software introduced one of the first commercially available implementations of SQL, Oracle V2 (Version2) for VAX computers.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] By 1986, ANSI and ISO standard groups officially adopted the standard "Database Language SQL" language definition.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] SQL implementations are incompatible between vendors and do not necessarily completely follow standards.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] In particular, date and time syntax, string concatenation, `NULL`s, and comparison case sensitivity vary from vendor to vendor.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] PostgreSQL and Mimer SQL strive for standards compliance, though PostgreSQL does not adhere to the standard in all cases.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] For example, the folding of unquoted names to lower case in PostgreSQL is incompatible with the SQL standard, which says that unquoted names should be folded to upper case.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] Thus, according to the standard, `Foo` should be equivalent to `FOO`, not `foo`.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] Popular implementations of SQL commonly omit support for basic features of Standard SQL, such as the `DATE` or `TIME` data types.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] The most obvious such examples, and incidentally the most popular commercial and proprietary SQL DBMSs, are Oracle (whose `DATE` behaves as `DATETIME`, and lacks a `TIME` type) and MS SQL Server (before the 2008 version).
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] As a result, SQL code can rarely be ported between database systems without modifications.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] SQL was adopted as a standard by the ANSI in 1986 as SQL-86 and the ISO in 1987.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] It is maintained by *ISO/IEC JTC 1, Information technology, Subcommittee SC 32, Data management and interchange*.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] Until 1996, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) data-management standards program certified SQL DBMS compliance with the SQL standard.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] Vendors now self-certify the compliance of their products.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] The original standard declared that the official pronunciation for "SQL" was an initialism: /ˌɛsˌkjuːˈɛl/ ("ess cue el").
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] Regardless, many English-speaking database professionals (including Donald Chamberlin himself) use the acronym-like pronunciation of /ˈsiːkwəl/ ("sequel"), mirroring the language's prerelease development name, "SEQUEL".
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] The standard is commonly denoted by the pattern: *ISO/IEC 9075-n:yyyy Part n: title*, or, as a shortcut, *ISO/IEC 9075*.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] Interested parties may purchase the standards documents from ISO, IEC, or ANSI.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] SQL is designed for a specific purpose: to query data contained in a relational database.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] SQL is a set-based, declarative programming language, not an imperative programming language like C or BASIC.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] However, extensions to Standard SQL add procedural programming language functionality, such as control-of-flow constructs.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] In addition to the standard SQL/PSM extensions and proprietary SQL extensions, procedural and object-oriented programmability is available on many SQL platforms via DBMS integration with other languages.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] The SQL standard defines SQL/JRT extensions (SQL Routines and Types for the Java Programming Language) to support Java code in SQL databases.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] Microsoft SQL Server 2005 uses the SQLCLR (SQL Server Common Language Runtime) to host managed .NET assemblies in the database, while prior versions of SQL Server were restricted to unmanaged extended stored procedures primarily written in C.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] PostgreSQL lets users write functions in a wide variety of languages—including Perl, Python, Tcl, JavaScript (PL/V8) and C.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] A distinction should be made between alternatives to SQL as a language, and alternatives to the relational model itself.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] Below are proposed relational alternatives to the SQL language.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] See navigational database and NoSQL for alternatives to the relational model.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] Distributed Relational Database Architecture (DRDA) was designed by a workgroup within IBM from 1988 to 1994.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] DRDA enables network-connected relational databases to cooperate to fulfill SQL requests.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] An interactive user or program can issue SQL statements to a local RDB and receive tables of data and status indicators in reply from remote RDBs.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] SQL statements can also be compiled and stored in remote RDBs as packages and then invoked by package name.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] This is important for the efficient operation of application programs that issue complex, high-frequency queries.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] It is especially important when the tables to be accessed are located in remote systems.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] Distributed SQL processing ala DRDA is distinctive from contemporary distributed SQL databases.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] SQL deviates in several ways from its theoretical foundation, the relational model and its tuple calculus.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] In that model, a table is a set of tuples, while in SQL, tables and query results are lists of rows; the same row may occur multiple times, and the order of rows can be employed in queries (e.g., in the `LIMIT` clause).
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] Critics argue that SQL should be replaced with a language that returns strictly to the original foundation: for example, see *The Third Manifesto* by Hugh Darwen and C.J.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] Early specifications did not support major features, such as primary keys.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] Result sets could not be named, and subqueries had not been defined.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] The lack of sum types has been described as a roadblock to full use of SQL's user-defined types.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] JSON support, for example, needed to be added by a new standard in 2016.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] The concept of Null is the subject of some debate.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] The Null marker indicates the absence of a value, and is distinct from a value of 0 for an integer column or an empty string for a text column.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] The concept of Nulls enforces the 3-valued-logic in SQL, which is a concrete implementation of the general 3-valued logic.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] Another popular criticism is that it allows duplicate rows, making integration with languages such as Python, whose data types might make accurately representing the data difficult, in terms of parsing and by the absence of modularity.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] This is usually avoided by declaring a primary key, or a unique constraint, with one or more columns that uniquely identify a row in the table.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sql] In a sense similar to object–relational impedance mismatch, a mismatch occurs between the declarative SQL language and the procedural languages in which SQL is typically embedded.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sqlalchemy] SQLAlchemy offers tools for database schema generation, querying, and object-relational mapping.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sqlalchemy] SQLAlchemy was first released in February 2006.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sqlalchemy] It has evolved to include a wide range of features for database interaction and has gained popularity among Python developers.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sqlalchemy] The following example represents an n-to-1 relationship between movies and their directors.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/sqlalchemy] It is shown how user-defined Python classes create corresponding database tables, how instances with relationships are created from either side of the relationship, and finally how the data can be queried — illustrating automatically generated SQL queries for both lazy and eager loading.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/tutorial-index] The SQLAlchemy Unified Tutorial is integrated between the Core and ORM components of SQLAlchemy and serves as a unified introduction to SQLAlchemy as a whole.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/tutorial-index] For users of SQLAlchemy within the 1.x series, in the 2.0 style of working, the ORM uses Core-style querying with the `select()` construct, and transactional semantics between Core connections and ORM sessions are equivalent.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/tutorial-index] Take note of the blue border styles for each section, that will tell you how “ORM-ish” a particular topic is!
[src:sqlalchemy-core/tutorial-index] Users who are already familiar with SQLAlchemy, and especially those looking to migrate existing applications to work under the SQLAlchemy 2.0 series within the 1.4 transitional phase should check out the SQLAlchemy 2.0 - Major Migration Guide document as well.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/tutorial-index] For the newcomer, this document has a **lot** of detail, however by the end they will be considered an **Alchemist**.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/tutorial-index] SQLAlchemy is presented as two distinct APIs, one building on top of the other.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/tutorial-index] These APIs are known as **Core** and **ORM**.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/tutorial-index] Sections that are **primarily Core-only** will not refer to the ORM.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/tutorial-index] SQLAlchemy constructs used in these sections will be imported from the `sqlalchemy` namespace.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/tutorial-index] As an additional indicator of subject classification, they will also include a **dark blue border on the right**.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/tutorial-index] When using the ORM, these concepts are still in play but are less often explicit in user code.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/tutorial-index] ORM users should read these sections, but not expect to be using these APIs directly for ORM-centric code.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/tutorial-index] Sections that are **primarily ORM-only** should be **titled to include the phrase “ORM”**, so that it’s clear this is an ORM related topic.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/tutorial-index] SQLAlchemy constructs used in these sections will be imported from the `sqlalchemy.orm` namespace.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/tutorial-index] Finally, as an additional indicator of subject classification, they will also include a **light blue border on the left**.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/tutorial-index] For each of these sections, there will be **introductory text** discussing the degree to which ORM users should expect to be using these programming patterns.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/tutorial-index] SQLAlchemy constructs in these sections will be imported from the `sqlalchemy` namespace with some potential use of `sqlalchemy.orm` constructs at the same time.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/tutorial-index] As an additional indicator of subject classification, these sections will also include **both a thinner light border on the left, and a thicker dark border on the right**.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/tutorial-index] Core and ORM users should familiarize with concepts in these sections equally.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/tutorial-index] The tutorial will present both concepts in the natural order that they should be learned, first with a mostly-Core-centric approach and then spanning out into more ORM-centric concepts.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/tutorial-index] This tutorial is written using a system called doctest.
[src:sqlalchemy-core/tutorial-index] All of the code excerpts written with a `>>>` are actually run as part of SQLAlchemy’s test suite, and the reader is invited to work with the code examples given in real time with their own Python interpreter.
